  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties:\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance:\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition agreements for financial criminals\n\n3. Compliance Requirements:\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk jurisdictions\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization:\n- Countries align their national laws with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar prosecution mechanisms\n- Comparable penalties and sanctions\n\n5. Information Sharing Mechanisms:\n- International financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated monitoring of financial transactions\n- Cross-border investigative cooperation\n\nThese intersections create a complex framework for preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
